ant economic policy changes of the 1980s. Through a detailed examination of voting patterns, monetary and fiscal policies, welfare spending, tax reform, minimum wage legislation, the savings and loan collapse, and international trade policy, the authors explore how politics can influence the direction of economic policymaking.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEconomics -- Political aspects -- United States. 0aUnited States -- Economic policy -- 1981-1993 -- Decision making. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  apolitics, political economy, economics, united states of america, usa, american government, 20th century, policymaking, voting patterns, monetary, fiscal, welfare, spending, tax, taxation, reform, laws, legality, legislation, politicians, minimum wage, savings, loans, trade policy, decision making, elections, democrats, republicans, parties, budget, governance, thrift.1 aAlesina, Alberto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlesina, Alberto, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAlt, James E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarliner, Geoffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarliner, Geoffrey, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDestler, I. M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerejohn, John A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFiorina, Morris P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCubbins, Mathew D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPoole, Keith T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRomer, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRosenthal, Ho